has to deal a little bit

00:38:14.460 --> 00:38:18.030
with wallpaper racism.

00:38:18.030 --> 00:38:23.010
So I tutor middle school
and high school students

00:38:23.010 --> 00:38:23.930
with Solid Ground.

00:38:23.930 --> 00:38:26.950
So these are all
underprivileged children, mostly

00:38:26.950 --> 00:38:28.290
children of color.

00:38:28.290 --> 00:38:31.020
And what you see is that
when they go to school,

00:38:31.020 --> 00:38:35.010
they have lowered expectations
from their teachers, it seems.

00:38:35.010 --> 00:38:40.450
And apart from your teachers and
the people that are helping you

00:38:40.450 --> 00:38:43.115
there, usually you get these
expectations from your parents.

00:38:43.115 --> 00:38:45.240
But they don't always have
a great family structure

00:38:45.240 --> 00:38:46.540
for that.

00:38:46.540 --> 00:38:50.970
Often times, the child will have
parents that neither of them

00:38:50.970 --> 00:38:53.180
graduated high school,
and they don't really care

00:38:53.180 --> 00:38:54.760
about their child's education.

00:38:54.760 --> 00:38:58.640
And so I guess, what
are your suggestions

00:38:58.640 --> 00:39:03.550
for helping put expectations on
them so that they can succeed?

00:39:03.550 --> 00:39:05.050
Because what I see
is that when they

00:39:05.050 --> 00:39:07.700
don't have the expectations,
they don't typically succeed.

00:39:07.700 --> 00:39:09.460
And when they do
have expectations,

00:39:09.460 --> 00:39:14.420
they do succeed, because they
are almost always smart enough

00:39:14.420 --> 00:39:17.870
to do what they need to do.

00:39:17.870 --> 00:39:19.310
No one's telling them they are.

00:39:19.310 --> 00:39:20.600
I

00:39:20.600 --> 00:39:22.620
KAREEM ABDUL-JABBAR:
Well, I think

00:39:22.620 --> 00:39:25.170
the problem that
you're identifying

00:39:25.170 --> 00:39:28.280
has to do-- the lowered
expectations are often

00:39:28.280 --> 00:39:32.740
accompanied by teachers
who see lowered

00:39:32.740 --> 00:39:37.080
expectations in the poor
kids that they teach.

00:39:37.080 --> 00:39:41.760
So they use the discipline
issue to try and deal

00:39:41.760 --> 00:39:46.060
with that to get
them to do something

00:39:46.060 --> 00:39:48.760
instead of giving
them the opportunity

00:39:48.760 --> 00:39:51.920
to overcome the gap.

00:39:51.920 --> 00:39:55.600
So if their parents
don't have an education

00:39:55.600 --> 00:39:57.600
and don't see that
as important, you

00:39:57.600 --> 00:40:03.160
can still transfer the
values that you have that

00:40:03.160 --> 00:40:05.700
enabled you to get to the
position where you are.

00:40:05.700 --> 00:40:07.480
You can transfer
that to the kids.

00:40:07.480 --> 00:40:10.610
They don't have to be
like their parents.

00:40:10.610 --> 00:40:16.480
But so many times, people just
think it's a genetic thing,

00:40:16.480 --> 00:40:18.242
and that's it.

00:40:18.242 --> 00:40:20.200
And some of the brightest
people in our country

00:40:20.200 --> 00:40:23.939
come from absolutely
horrible circumstances.

00:40:23.939 --> 00:40:25.980
And they overcome it just
because they're bright,

00:40:25.980 --> 00:40:31.210
and they recognize their own
ambition, and they go for it.

00:40:31.210 --> 00:40:40.330
So I think that you can't ever
have an attitude where you

00:40:40.330 --> 00:40:42.690
won't be pleasantly surprised.

00:40:42.690 --> 00:40:46.840
You've got to allow for
that to happen as a teacher.

00:40:46.840 --> 00:40:53.220
And if we can get that
idea across to the people

00:40:53.220 --> 00:40:59.130
in power that make all these
things happen or not happen,

00:40:59.130 --> 00:41:01.200
I think we can do a better job.

00:41:01.200 --> 00:41:04.710
But raising people up
from poverty and ignorance

00:41:04.710 --> 00:41:07.220
is really a very tough thing.

00:41:07.220 --> 00:41:10.280
And it also would
require that people

00:41:10.280 --> 00:41:13.250
are willing to spend money
to get the good teachers who

00:41:13.250 --> 00:41:16.720
don't want to be involved
in it because they're not

00:41:16.720 --> 00:41:20.210
appreciated, and they're
underpaid, and why bother?

00:41:20.210 --> 00:41:23.390
I think we've gotten
to this point.

00:41:23.390 --> 00:41:27.650
The American education
system, for so long,

00:41:27.650 --> 00:41:28.740
was the best in the world.

00:41:28.740 --> 00:41:33.030
Our high school students
had the best grades

00:41:33.030 --> 00:41:35.300
of all the industrialized
countries in the world.

00:41:35.300 --> 00:41:39.350
And now we're down 6th or 7th
place, 8th, 9th, 10th place,

00:41:39.350 --> 00:41:41.640
just because people
aren't going to spend

00:41:41.640 --> 00:41:44.940
the money for the good teachers
and give them the opportunity

00:41:44.940 --> 00:41:48.850
to do the things that they
have done so well for decades.

00:41:48.850 --> 00:41:51.760
Sometime in the '70s or '80s,
they just threw their hands up

00:41:51.760 --> 00:41:53.550
and said, forget it.

00:41:53.550 --> 00:41:56.340
And I think we paid
a price for that.

00:41:56.340 --> 00:41:57.930
So I hope that changes.

00:41:57.930 --> 00:41:58.720
AUDIENCE: I agree.

00:41:58.720 --> 00:41:58.970
