from the Republicans

00:51:08.240 --> 00:51:10.870
just because he
was a black person,

00:51:10.870 --> 00:51:13.050
and he whipped them twice.

00:51:13.050 --> 00:51:15.930
And they can't stand that.

00:51:15.930 --> 00:51:17.530
That's really what
it's all about.

00:51:17.530 --> 00:51:19.820
They can't stand the
way that he beat them.

00:51:19.820 --> 00:51:23.100
He was smarter than they were
and understood the issues

00:51:23.100 --> 00:51:26.700
and did a better job in
addressing the American people

00:51:26.700 --> 00:51:28.810
about the things
that concerned them,

00:51:28.810 --> 00:51:31.280
and the Republicans haven't
been able to do that.

00:51:31.280 --> 00:51:36.350
They keep coming up with the
same BS about trickle-down.

00:51:36.350 --> 00:51:39.200
We take taxes off of
the wealthiest people,

00:51:39.200 --> 00:51:40.600
and jobs will trickle down.

00:51:40.600 --> 00:51:42.320
That hasn't happened ever.

00:51:42.320 --> 00:51:44.020
And they keep repeating this.

00:51:44.020 --> 00:51:46.690
And it's horse crap you know.

00:51:46.690 --> 00:51:52.140
So they've used that as an
excuse to oppose everything

00:51:52.140 --> 00:51:53.370
that he's tried to do.

00:51:53.370 --> 00:51:58.260
And it's really
hamstrung his presidency.

00:51:58.260 --> 00:52:00.460
And in addition to
that, he has to be

00:52:00.460 --> 00:52:02.010
present for all Americans.

00:52:02.010 --> 00:52:04.930
He can't just be the
president for black Americans

00:52:04.930 --> 00:52:09.080
and just someone in the
job for white Americans.

00:52:09.080 --> 00:52:11.580
He has to do the best job
he can for all Americans

00:52:11.580 --> 00:52:13.670
and can't be seen
as being biased.

00:52:13.670 --> 00:52:17.240
And I think that, really, is
what you're talking about,

00:52:17.240 --> 00:52:21.280
where he could have been
more proactive for issues

00:52:21.280 --> 00:52:23.530
that are important to
minority communities.

00:52:23.530 --> 00:52:25.910
But if he did that, the
majority of the country

00:52:25.910 --> 00:52:30.500
would feel that he was
misusing his position.

00:52:30.500 --> 00:52:34.580
And you know he was really
handcuffed in that sense.

00:52:34.580 --> 00:52:37.620
But I'm so happy
that he got the job.

00:52:37.620 --> 00:52:40.720
And did what he has tried.

00:52:40.720 --> 00:52:44.010
And I hope that
people, over time,

00:52:44.010 --> 00:52:47.430
will appreciate him more,
just for the patience

00:52:47.430 --> 00:52:49.590
that he showed in
all this opposition.

00:52:49.590 --> 00:52:53.660
We can't even get another
Supreme Court Justice

00:52:53.660 --> 00:52:57.770
in because they don't want
to give him the opportunity

00:52:57.770 --> 00:53:00.210
because he might do something
that they don't like.

00:53:00.210 --> 00:53:03.830
And he did win that
election in 2012

00:53:03.830 --> 00:53:06.650
that enabled him to do that,
whether they like it or not.

00:53:06.650 --> 00:53:09.670
But they're not going
to acknowledge that.

00:53:09.670 --> 00:53:12.800
It's really the
double standard that

00:53:12.800 --> 00:53:16.890
applies to most people of
color that has traditionally

00:53:16.890 --> 00:53:18.500
been part of the
American way of life.

00:53:18.500 --> 00:53:20.587
And we got to get away from it.

00:53:20.587 --> 00:53:21.420
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:53:21.420 --> 00:53:24.250
KAREEM ABDUL-JABBAR: Thank
you for the question.

00:53:24.250 --> 00:53:25.416
AUDIENCE: Thanks for coming.

00:53:25.416 --> 00:53:27.140
I'll try to make my setup short.

00:53:27.140 --> 00:53:29.200
This touches on
themes-- you mentioned

00:53:29.200 --> 00:53:31.450
that we need to solve the
problem of income inequality

00:53:31.450 --> 00:53:32.820
and wealth inequality.

00:53:32.820 --> 00:53:34.320
And some of the
previous questioners

00:53:34.320 --> 00:53:37.130
also brought up the
ideas of visibility,

00:53:37.130 --> 00:53:39.826
that people who are not
experiencing oppression,

00:53:39.826 --> 00:53:41.200
even if they're
well-intentioned,

00:53:41.200 --> 00:53:43.390
may not be aware
of its existence

00:53:43.390 --> 00:53:45.530
and may think that
some of the people who

00:53:45.530 --> 00:53:47.985
are speaking about it are
blowing it out proportion

00:53:47.985 --> 00:53:51.310
and that kind of stuff.

00:53:51.310 --> 00:53:53.709
So because of that,
I think some issues

00:53:53.709 --> 00:53:55.250
that come up that
are very important,

00:53:55.250 --> 00:54:00.230
things like affirmative
action and reparations,

00:54:00.230 --> 00:54:02.862
you see people classify
that as reverse racism

00:54:02.862 --> 00:54:05.070
and that we have this sort
of myth of color blindness

00:54:05.070 --> 00:54:09.860
that everybody-- I guess
if they don't experience

00:54:09.860 --> 00:54:15.630
the un-level playing field of
lack of opportunities a lot

00:54:15.630 --> 00:54:18.780
of people are experiencing,
they think it sort of propagates

00:54:18.780 --> 00:54:21.210
these myths of if people
just worked harder,

00:54:21.210 --> 00:54:23.350
they would get the things
that my parents had

00:54:23.350 --> 00:54:25.520
to work hard to get.

00:54:25.520 --> 00:54:27.820
So I guess the specific
question I was wondering

00:54:27.820 --> 00:54:30.404
is if you have a position,
specifically, on reparations,

00:54:30.404 --> 00:54:31.820
whether you think
that's something

00:54:31.820 --> 00:54:34.516
that our government should be--

00:54:34.516 --> 00:54:36.640
KAREEM ABDUL-JABBAR: I
don't think that reparations

00:54:36.640 --> 00:54:39.490
are appropriate, because
there's nobody alive now

00:54:39.490 --> 00:54:41.690
that owned slaves.

00:54:41.690 --> 00:54:44.660
Those people, they
got away with that.

00:54:44.660 --> 00:54:46.490
So there's nothing
we can do about that.

00:54:46.490 --> 00:54:52.450
But I think that because,
especially people of color,

00:54:52.450 --> 00:54:58.860
are so economically far behind,
that an educational effort

00:54:58.860 --> 00:55:01.900
focused on the communities
of people of color

00:55:01.900 --> 00:55:05.030
to get them to the point
where they can compete

00:55:05.030 --> 00:55:08.000
for good jobs and
economic opportunities--

00:55:08.000 --> 00:55:11.950
I think people
could accept that,

00:55:11.950 --> 00:55:15.040
because these people
have inherited

00:55:15.040 --> 00:55:19.890
an inferior position
economically for something

00:55:19.890 --> 00:55:21.370
that they didn't do.

00:55:21.370 --> 00:55:25.890
And it can be remedied
through education.

00:55:25.890 --> 00:55:30.230
Their kids will have the
education and the opportunity

00:55:30.230 --> 00:55:33.640
to do much better and
have some catch up.

00:55:33.640 --> 00:55:37.470
But there's nothing we can do
about what happened in 1845.

00:55:37.470 --> 00:55:39.200
There's nothing we
can do about that.

00:55:39.200 --> 00:55:43.620
And I don't feel that I
can hold any white person

00:55:43.620 --> 00:55:44.780
responsible for that.

00:55:44.780 --> 00:55:46.380
It just doesn't work.

00:55:46.380 --> 00:55:48.340
I'm glad people like
Georgetown University

00:55:48.340 --> 00:55:52.390
are acknowledging
their culpability

00:55:52.390 --> 00:55:53.620
and doing something about it.

00:55:53.620 --> 00:55:59.630
And again, they're going to
have some scholarships for kids

00:55:59.630 --> 00:56:02.750
from black neighborhoods
that need it to give them

00:56:02.750 --> 00:56:06.910
the educational opportunity that
will enable them to overcome

00:56:06.910 --> 00:56:08.240
something that they inherited.

00:56:08.240 --> 00:56:10.290
So I think that's
the only way to go

00:56:10.290 --> 00:56:13.190
about it without being unfair.

00:56:13.190 --> 00:56:19.230
And I hope overall, throughout
the communities in our country,

00:56:19.230 --> 00:56:23.235
we start to see that and
make the adjustments.

00:56:23.235 --> 00:56:24.360
Thank you for you question.

00:56:24.360 --> 00:56:25.300
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

